

<worksheet xml:id="A02_Exponential_Growth_Decay">
  <title>Math 150  Activity 02: Exponential growth and decay</title>
  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>Doubling time</em>
        is the time required for an exponentially increasing quantity to double.
      </p>

      <task xml:id="x2formsexp">
        <p>
          Write two general forms for an exponential function.
        </p>

        <p>
          ( <xref ref="x2formsexp"></xref>1) <fillin characters="10"/>
        </p>

        <p>
          ( <xref ref="x2formsexp"></xref>2) <fillin characters="10"/>
        </p>
      </task>

      <task>
        <p>
          If you start with 1 unit of such a quantity,
          how much will you have at the end of the doubling time?
        </p>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="findexpmodel">
        <p>
          Find an exponential model for a quantity with a doubling time of 3 hours.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          You used one of the two forms you listed in<nbsp /><xref ref="x2formsexp" /> for your answer in<nbsp /><xref ref="findexpmodel" />.
          Now write a function for the same quantity from<nbsp /><xref ref="findexpmodel" /> using the other form.
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise workspace="50%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the doubling time of a quantity that is increasing by 5<percent /> per year.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>Compound interest.</em>
      </p>

      <task xml:id="bankacct">
        <p>
          Find the formula for the amount in a bank account that pays 2<percent /> interest annually if <dollar />1000 is invested today.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          If no further deposits and no withdrawals are made,
          how much is in the account from<nbsp /><xref ref="bankacct" /> 10 years after the initial investment?
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="50%">
        <p>
          When will the balance in the account be <dollar />1500?
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If an investment has interest which is compounded <em>continuously</em>,
        the general formula is <m>P=P_0 e^{rt}</m>,
        where <m>P_0</m> is the amount initially invested,
        <m>P</m> is the amount in the account after <m>t</m> years and <m>r</m> is the annual interest rate in decimal (assuming no other deposits or withdrawals are made.)
      </p>

      <p>
        If you invest <dollar />5000 at 2.5<percent /> compounded continuously,
        how long will it take before the balance in the account is <dollar />12,000?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>Half-life</em> is the time required for a quantity that is decaying exponentially to decrease by one-half of its present value.
      </p>

      <task xml:id="halflife">
        <p>
          The half-life of a certain exponentially decaying quantity is 10 years.
          If the starting amount is 10 grams,
          find the formula for the amount left <m>t</m> years later.
          Use: <m>Q=Q_0 e^{kt}</m>.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task>
        <p>
          Repeat part<nbsp /><xref ref="halflife" /> if instead the half-life is 500 years.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task>
        <p>
          In general,
          how do you find <m>k</m> for a quantity with a half-life of <m>h</m> years?
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>

